[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy 1.0 was released on January 2, 2007, and Groovy 2.0 in July, 2012.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Since version 2, Groovy can be compiled statically, offering type inference and performance near that of Java.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy 2.4 was the last major release under Pivotal Software's sponsorship which ended in March 2015.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy has since changed its governance structure to a Project Management Committee in the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] James Strachan first talked about the development of Groovy on his blog in August 2003.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] In March 2004, Groovy was submitted to the Java Community Process (JCP) as JSR 241 and accepted by ballot.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Several versions were released between 2004 and 2006.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] After the JCP standardization effort began, the version numbering changed, and a version called "1.0" was released on January 2, 2007.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] After various betas and release candidates numbered 1.1, on December 7, 2007, Groovy 1.1 Final was released and immediately renumbered as Groovy 1.5 to reflect the many changes made.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] In 2007, Groovy won the first prize at JAX 2007 innovation award.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] In 2008, Grails, a Groovy web framework, won the second prize at JAX 2008 innovation award.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] In November 2008, SpringSource acquired the Groovy and Grails company (G2One).
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] In August 2009 VMware acquired SpringSource.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] In April 2012, after eight years of inactivity, the Spec Lead changed the status of JSR 241 to dormant.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Strachan had left the project silently a year before the Groovy 1.0 release in 2007.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] In Oct 2016, Strachan stated "I still love groovy (jenkins pipelines are so groovy!), java, go, typescript and kotlin".
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] On July 2, 2012, Groovy 2.0 was released, which, among other new features, added static compiling and static type checking.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] When the Pivotal Software joint venture was spun-off by EMC Corporation (EMC) and VMware in April 2013, Groovy and Grails formed part of its product portfolio.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Pivotal ceased sponsoring Groovy and Grails from April 2015.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] That same month, Groovy changed its governance structure from a Codehaus repository to a Project Management Committee (PMC) in the Apache Software Foundation via its incubator.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy graduated from Apache's incubator and became a top-level project in November 2015.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] On February 7, 2020, Groovy 3.0 was released.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Version 4.0 was released on January 25, 2022.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Most valid Java files are also valid Groovy files.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Although the two languages are similar, Groovy code can be more compact, because it does not need all the elements that Java needs.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] This makes it possible for Java programmers to learn Groovy gradually by starting with familiar Java syntax before acquiring more Groovy programming idioms.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy natively supports markup languages such as XML and HTML by using an inline Document Object Model (DOM) syntax.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] This feature enables the definition and manipulation of many types of heterogeneous data assets with a uniform and concise syntax and programming methodology.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Unlike Java, a Groovy source code file can be executed as an (uncompiled) script, if it contains code outside any class definition, if it is a class with a *main* method, or if it is a *Runnable* or *GroovyTestCase*.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] A Groovy script is fully parsed, compiled, and generated before executing (similar to Python and Ruby).
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] This occurs under the hood, and the compiled version is not saved as an artifact of the process.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy offers simple, consistent syntax for handling *lists* and *maps*, reminiscent of Java's *array* syntax.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy offers support for prototype extension through `ExpandoMetaClass`, Extension Modules (only in Groovy 2), Objective-C-like Categories and `DelegatingMetaClass`.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy's changes in code through prototyping are not visible in Java, since each attribute/method invocation in Groovy goes through the metaclass registry.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] The changed code can only be accessed from Java by going to the metaclass registry.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy also allows overriding methods as `getProperty()`, `propertyMissing()` among others, enabling the developer to intercept calls to an object and specify an action for them, in a simplified aspect-oriented way.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] The Grails framework uses metaprogramming extensively to enable GORM dynamic finders, like `User.findByName('Josh')` and others.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy's syntax permits omitting parentheses and dots in some situations.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] enabling the development of domain-specific languages (DSLs) that look like plain English.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Although Groovy is mostly an object-oriented language, it also offers functional programming features.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] According to Groovy's documentation: "Closures in Groovy work similar to a 'method pointer', enabling code to be written and run in a later point in time".
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy's closures support free variables, i.e. variables that have not been explicitly passed as a parameter to it, but exist in its declaration context, partial application (that it terms 'currying'), delegation, implicit, typed and untyped parameters.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Usually called *partial application*, this Groovy feature allows closures' parameters to be set to a default parameter in any of their arguments, creating a new closure with the bound value.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Supplying one argument to the `curry()` method will fix argument one.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Supplying N arguments will fix arguments 1 ..
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Curry can also be used in the reverse direction (fixing the last N arguments) using `rcurry()`.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Groovy also supports lazy evaluation, reduce/fold, infinite structures and immutability, among others.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] On JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) and XML processing, Groovy employs the Builder pattern, making the production of the data structure less verbose.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] and also can be processed in a streaming way through `StreamingMarkupBuilder`.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] To change the implementation to JSON, the `MarkupBuilder` can be swapped to `JsonBuilder`.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] GStrings containing variables and expressions must be declared using double quotes.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] A complex expression must be enclosed in curly brackets.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] According to Groovy's own documentation, "When the Groovy compiler compiles Groovy scripts and classes, at some point in the process, the source code will end up being represented in memory in the form of a Concrete Syntax Tree, then transformed into an Abstract Syntax Tree.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] The purpose of AST Transformations is to let developers hook into the compilation process to be able to modify the AST before it is turned into bytecode that will be run by the JVM.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] The testing framework Spock uses AST transformations to allow the programmer to write tests in a syntax not supported by Groovy, but the relevant code is then manipulated in the AST to valid code.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Traits can be seen as interfaces carrying both default implementations and state.
[src:grails-framework/apache-groovy] Traits allow a wide range of abilities, from simple composition to testing.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] The concept was introduced by David Heinemeier Hansson to describe the philosophy of the Ruby on Rails web framework, but is related to earlier ideas like the concept of "sensible defaults" and the principle of least astonishment in user interface design.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] The phrase essentially means a developer only needs to specify unconventional aspects of the application.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] For example, if there is a class Sales in the model, the corresponding table in the database is called "sales" by default.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] It is only if one deviates from this convention, such as the table "product sales", that one needs to write code regarding these names.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] When the convention implemented by the tool matches the desired behavior, it behaves as expected without having to write configuration files.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] Only when the desired behavior deviates from the implemented convention is explicit configuration required.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] Ruby on Rails' use of the phrase is particularly focused on its default project file and directory structure, which prevent developers from having to write XML configuration files to specify which modules the framework should load, which was common in many earlier frameworks.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] Other methods of decreasing the number of decisions a developer needs to make include programming idioms and configuration libraries with a multilayered architecture.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] Some frameworks need multiple configuration files, each with many settings.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] These provide information specific to each project, ranging from URLs to mappings between classes and database tables.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] Many configuration files with many parameters are often difficult to maintain.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] For example, early versions of the Java persistence mapper Hibernate mapped entities and their fields to the database by describing these relationships in XML files.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] Most of this information could have been revealed by conventionally mapping class names to the identically named database tables and the fields to their columns, respectively.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] Later versions did away with the XML configuration file and instead employed these very conventions, deviations from which can be indicated through the use of Java annotations (see JavaBeans specification, linked below).
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] Many modern frameworks use a *convention over configuration* approach.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] The concept is older, however, dating back to the concept of a default, and can be spotted more recently in the roots of Java libraries.
[src:grails-framework/convention-over-configuration] For example, the JavaBeans specification relies on it heavily.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails was previously known as "Groovy on Rails"; in March 2006 that name was dropped in response to a request by David Heinemeier Hansson, founder of the Ruby on Rails framework.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Work began in July 2005, with the 0.1 release on March 29, 2006, and the 1.0 release announced on February 18, 2008.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Creating web applications in Java traditionally involves configuring environments and frameworks at the start and during development.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] This configuration is very often externalized in XML files to ease configuration and avoid embedding configuration in application code.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] XML was initially welcomed as it provided greater consistency to configure applications.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] However, in recent years, it has become apparent that although XML is great for configuration, it can be tedious to set up an environment.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] This may reduce productivity as developers spend time understanding and maintaining framework configuration as the application grows.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Adding or changing functionality in applications that use XML configuration adds an extra step to the change process, which slows down productivity and may diminish the agility of the entire process.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails removes the need to add configuration in XML files.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Instead, the framework uses a set of rules or conventions while inspecting the code of Grails-based applications.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] For example, a class name that ends with `Controller` (for example `BookController`) is considered a web controller.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] When using traditional Java web toolkits, it's up to developers to assemble development units, which can be tedious.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails provides a development environment that includes a web server to get developers started right away.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] All required libraries are part of the Grails distribution, and Grails prepares the Java web environment for deployment automatically.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails features dynamic methods on several classes through mixins.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] A mixin is a method that is added to a class dynamically, as if the functionality had been compiled into the program.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] These dynamic methods allow developers to perform operations without having to implement interfaces or extend base classes.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails provides dynamic methods based on the type of class.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The Grails web framework has been designed according to the MVC paradigm.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails uses controllers to implement the behavior of web pages.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The controller above has a `list` action which returns a model containing all books in the database.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] This command creates a class in the `grails-app/controller` directory of the Grails project.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Creating the controller class is sufficient to have it recognized by Grails.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The `list` action maps to `http://localhost:8080/book/list` in development mode.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] This view should be saved as `grails-app/views/book/list.gsp` of the Grails project.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] This location maps to the `BookController` and `list` action.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Placing the file in this location is sufficient to have it recognized by Grails.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails provides a large number of tag libraries out of the box.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The `formatDate` tag library above formats a `java.util.Date` object to a `String`.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] This tag library should be added to the `grails-app/taglib/ApplicationTagLib.groovy` file or a file ending with `TagLib.groovy` in the `grails-app/taglib` directory.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] To use a dynamic tag library in a GSP no import tags have to be used.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The domain model in Grails is GORM (Grails Object Relational Mapping).
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] This command requests the domain class name and creates the appropriate file.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Creating this class is all that is required to have it managed for persistence by Grails.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] With Grails 0.3, GORM has been improved and e.g. adds the properties id and version itself to the domain class if they are not present.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The id property is used as the primary key of the corresponding table.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The version property is used for optimistic locking.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Note that the query syntax is Hibernate HQL.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails supports scaffolding to support CRUD operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete).
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] By creating this class you can perform CRUD operations on `http://localhost:8080/book`.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] This works because the BookController follows the same naming convention as the Book domain class.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Currently Grails does not provide scaffolding for associations.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The persistence mechanism in GORM is implemented via Hibernate.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] As such, legacy databases may be mapped to GORM classes using standard Hibernate mapping files.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails is built on top of and is part of the Java platform meaning that it is very easy to integrate with Java libraries, frameworks and existing code bases.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails offers transparent integration of classes which are mapped with the Hibernate ORM framework.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] One consequence of this is that scaffolding can be configured for Java classes mapped with Hibernate.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Another consequence is that the capabilities of the Grails web framework are fully available for these classes and the applications which use them.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails also makes use of the Spring Inversion of Control Framework; Grails is actually a Spring MVC application under the hood.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The Spring framework can be used to provision additional Spring beans and introduce them into the context of the application.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] The SiteMesh framework is used to manage the presentation layer, simplifying the development of pages via a robust templating system.
[src:grails-framework/grails-framework] Grails applications are packaged as war artifacts that can be deployed to any servlet container or Java EE application servers.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:grails-framework/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:grails-framework/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
